    <!-- AFFILIATE DISCLAIMER -->
    <AffiliateDisclaimer />

    <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
    <h2 id="why-energy-gummies">Why Energy Gummies Dominate Endurance Fueling in 2026</h2>

    <p>During exercise lasting longer than 60 minutes, glycogen stores become the limiting factor in performance. The human body stores approximately 2,000 calories of glycogen in muscle and liver — enough for roughly 90-120 minutes of moderate-to-high-intensity exercise. Once glycogen is depleted, the body shifts to fat oxidation, which cannot sustain high-intensity output. This metabolic wall — the infamous "bonk" — can be delayed or prevented entirely through strategic carbohydrate ingestion during exercise.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">90g/hr</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the maximum carbohydrate absorption rate achievable with dual-source (glucose + fructose) fueling, according to research by <strong>Jeukendrup et al.</strong> published in the Journal of Applied Physiology. This 40% increase over the 60g/hour single-source limit has fundamentally changed marathon and Ironman nutrition strategies, and energy gummies are the most portable format for hitting these targets during competition.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Energy gummies solve the three biggest problems with traditional fueling formats. Unlike gels, they do not require water to wash down and they provide a satisfying chewing action that many athletes prefer during long efforts. Unlike bars, they digest rapidly without diverting blood flow from working muscles to the gut. And unlike sports drinks alone, they deliver concentrated carbohydrates in a portable, pocket-sized format that does not slosh or spill during high-intensity movement.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Rapid Glycogen Delivery</h3>
        <p>Energy gummies deliver 20-25g of fast-absorbing carbohydrates per serving. Maltodextrin and glucose polymers are absorbed via the SGLT1 transporter and converted to muscle glycogen within 15-20 minutes of ingestion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="droplet" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Electrolyte Replacement</h3>
        <p>Sodium losses during exercise range from 300-1200mg per hour depending on sweat rate and concentration. Top energy gummies include 100-450mg sodium per pack to prevent hyponatremia and maintain muscle contractility.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>GI-Friendly Format</h3>
        <p>Chewing initiates salivary amylase activity, beginning carbohydrate digestion in the mouth. This pre-processing reduces the osmotic load hitting the stomach, making gummies gentler on the GI tract than concentrated gels.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Titratable Dosing</h3>
        <p>Unlike gels (all-or-nothing), gummies allow you to eat 2-3 pieces every 15 minutes rather than an entire serving at once. This steady drip of carbohydrates maintains stable blood glucose without large spikes and crashes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2010 study in <em>Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise</em> compared energy chews to energy gels during an <strong>80-minute cycling time trial</strong> and found no significant difference in performance, blood glucose response, or GI distress at equivalent carbohydrate doses. The researchers concluded that energy chews are a viable and equally effective alternative to gels for endurance fueling.</p>
      <cite>Campbell et al., Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise, 2010</cite>
    </div>

