    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Energy Gummy Science: Carbohydrate Types, Absorption, and Fueling Strategies</h3>
      <p>Understanding how different carbohydrate sources are absorbed determines whether your fueling strategy helps or hinders performance. The science of dual-source carbohydrates has fundamentally changed endurance nutrition.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Maltodextrin (Glucose Polymer)</strong>
          <p>A chain of glucose molecules absorbed via the SGLT1 transporter. Maximum intestinal absorption rate: ~60g per hour. The most common carbohydrate in energy products. Rapidly elevates blood glucose and replenishes muscle glycogen. GI tolerance decreases at high intake rates.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Fructose (Dual-Source Component)</strong>
          <p>Absorbed via the GLUT5 transporter — completely independent of the SGLT1 pathway used by glucose. Adding fructose at a 2:1 glucose-to-fructose ratio increases total carb absorption to ~90g per hour. Essential for athletes targeting maximal fueling rates in ultra-endurance events.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Honey (Natural Dual-Source)</strong>
          <p>Naturally contains ~40% fructose and ~30% glucose, making it an inherent dual-source carbohydrate. Also provides trace minerals (potassium, magnesium) and prebiotics. Honey-based gummies offer dual-source benefits from a single whole-food ingredient.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Sodium (Electrolyte Critical)</strong>
          <p>Athletes lose 300-1200mg sodium per hour through sweat. Inadequate replacement causes hyponatremia (dangerously low blood sodium), muscle cramping, and cognitive impairment. Target 300-600mg sodium per hour during events exceeding 2 hours, adjusted for individual sweat rate and concentration.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Gut training protocol:</strong> Your gut's ability to absorb carbohydrates during exercise is trainable. Start at 30-40g per hour during training runs and increase by 5-10g per week over 4-6 weeks. A 2017 study in the <em>British Journal of Sports Medicine</em> confirmed that systematic gut training improved carbohydrate tolerance and absorption during exercise, enabling athletes to reach higher fueling rates without GI distress on race day.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Never try new nutrition on race day:</strong> This is the oldest and most important rule in endurance sports. Any energy gummy you plan to use in competition should be tested extensively during training at race pace and in similar environmental conditions. GI tolerance varies between brands, flavors, and even temperature conditions. Build your race nutrition plan over multiple training blocks, not the night before the event.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Energy Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon or the brand's direct store. No product was provided free of charge, and no brand was informed of this evaluation in advance.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified carbohydrate content and sources.</strong> We analyzed the nutrition and ingredient panels to confirm carbohydrate content per serving, identify single vs. dual-source carbohydrate profiles, and calculate the glucose-to-fructose ratio where applicable.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed electrolyte profiles.</strong> Sodium content per pack was verified against label claims. We scored products on whether their sodium levels were adequate for moderate (300-600mg/hr) and heavy (600-1200mg/hr) sweaters without requiring separate supplementation.</li>
        <li><strong>Tested GI tolerance during exercise.</strong> Four editorial team members (2 runners, 2 cyclists) used each product during training sessions of 90-180 minutes at Zone 2-3 intensity, documenting GI symptoms including bloating, nausea, cramping, and urgency on a standardized 0-10 scale.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluated real-world usability.</strong> Packaging was tested for one-handed opening, gummy texture was assessed across temperature ranges (40-90°F), and chewability during exercise was rated. Products that stuck to teeth or required excessive chewing while breathing hard received lower scores.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated cost-effectiveness.</strong> Price per pack, price per gram of carbohydrate, and projected cost for a 3-hour race (targeting 60g carbs/hour) were computed to enable accurate cross-product comparison for athletes planning race budgets.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

