    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Energy Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take energy gummies during a workout?</summary>
      <p>For pre-workout energy, take gummies 15-30 minutes before training. During endurance exercise lasting longer than 60 minutes, begin consuming at the 30-45 minute mark and continue every 20-30 minutes. The ACSM recommends 30-60g of carbs per hour for prolonged exercise, and up to 90g/hour for ultra-endurance events using dual-source carbohydrates. Start conservatively and increase based on GI tolerance.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are energy gummies better than energy gels?</summary>
      <p>Energy gummies and gels deliver similar carbohydrate content per serving (20-25g) but differ in texture and GI tolerance. Gummies are more palatable for many athletes and do not require water to wash down. Gels are faster to consume. A 2010 study in <em>Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise</em> found no significant performance difference between chews and gels at equivalent carb doses. Choose based on personal preference and stomach tolerance.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many carbs should I consume per hour during exercise?</summary>
      <p>Guidelines recommend 30-60g per hour for exercise lasting 1-2.5 hours. For events exceeding 2.5 hours, up to 90g/hour is recommended using dual-source carbs (glucose + fructose at 2:1 ratio). The SGLT1 transporter maxes out at ~60g/hr for glucose alone, but fructose uses a separate transporter (GLUT5), enabling total absorption of 90g/hr. Train your gut during long sessions before attempting high intake in competition.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do energy gummies cause stomach problems during running?</summary>
      <p>GI distress affects 30-50% of endurance athletes, but gummies are generally better tolerated than gels because chewing mixes carbs with saliva, initiating digestion earlier. To minimize issues: start fueling early, take small amounts frequently (every 15-20 min), stay hydrated, and practice your race nutrition during training so your gut adapts. Avoid high-fructose products if you are fructose-sensitive.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should energy gummies contain caffeine?</summary>
      <p>Caffeine improves endurance performance by 12-15% and reduces perceived exertion. Energy gummies with 20-50mg caffeine per serving provide a titratable dose. The optimal performance dose is 3-6mg/kg body weight. Caffeinated gummies are most useful in the second half of long events when central fatigue increases. Save caffeinated options for key moments rather than consuming them throughout.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between single-source and dual-source carb gummies?</summary>
      <p>Single-source gummies use only glucose-based carbs, absorbed via SGLT1 at a max of ~60g/hr. Dual-source gummies combine glucose and fructose, using two separate transporters (SGLT1 + GLUT5), enabling absorption up to 90g/hr. A landmark study showed glucose + fructose at 2:1 ratio increased carb oxidation by 40%. Dual-source products are superior for events exceeding 2.5 hours.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I use energy gummies for non-athletic activities?</summary>
      <p>Energy gummies are designed for athletic performance during active glycogen depletion. Using them for sedentary activities (desk work, studying) is not recommended because the concentrated simple sugars will cause blood glucose spikes and crashes. For mental energy, consider focus gummies with L-theanine or lion's mane instead. Energy gummies are specifically for situations where muscles are actively depleting glycogen stores.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How should I store energy gummies?</summary>
      <p>Store below 75°F (24°C) in a dry place. High temperatures cause melting and sticking. In hot races, keep gummies in a cooler or insulated pocket until needed. Cold temperatures make them harder to chew but do not damage them. For race day, use small zip-lock bags in accessible pockets. Some brands (Maurten, Clif) have packaging designed for one-handed opening during competition.</p>
    </details>

